findings.description:
The docstring on `pub fn dispatch` (primitives/mod.rs:32-51) says:

```
/// - Phase-1 executable primitives owned by G6-A (`READ`, `WRITE`,
///   `RESPOND`, `EMIT`) delegate to their per-primitive module.
/// - Phase-1 executable primitives owned by G6-B (`TRANSFORM`, `BRANCH`,
///   `ITERATE`, `CALL`) are dispatched by G6-B; today this module calls the
///   evaluator back via the unimplemented arms so `cargo check` passes in
///   parallel commits. G6-B replaces the unimplemented arms with real
///   executors.
```

But the actual match arms at lines 59-62 call the real executors:

```rust
PrimitiveKind::Transform => transform::execute(op),
PrimitiveKind::Branch => branch::execute(op),
PrimitiveKind::Iterate => iterate::execute(op, host),
PrimitiveKind::Call => call::execute(op, host),
```

A new contributor reading the docstring will assume G6-B is still a work-in-progress and that TRANSFORM / BRANCH / ITERATE / CALL don't run. The opposite is true. This is exactly the pattern R5 Step-5c flagged on compromises #1 and #5 — docstring ahead of (here: behind) the code.

Direct docstring quote from register_crud:

```
/// **Phase 1 scope**: the registration registers the handler id and
/// stores a minimal subgraph shape. Primitive-dispatch execution via
/// `call` is deferred to Phase 2 — `engine.call(&id, ...)` currently
/// returns `EngineError::NotImplemented`.
```

But `Engine::call` at engine.rs:655-660 calls `dispatch_call`, which builds a per-op subgraph, runs `benten_eval::Evaluator::run(&subgraph, input_value, self as &dyn PrimitiveHost)` at engine.rs:908-909, replays the pending-ops buffer as a single transaction, and returns a populated `Outcome`. This is the close of Named Compromise #8 (documented in the commit b70a9df + the module doc at host.rs:10-12 which explicitly says 'Closes Compromise #8').

The docstring mirrors the pre-compromise-#8 state. A new developer reading `register_crud` will believe their CRUD handler is inert. The code tells the opposite story and the tests (`tests/integration/exit_criteria_all_six.rs`, the full CRUD→listing→deletion path) demonstrate the contrary. This is exactly the R5-Step-5c class of problem.

The module docstring lists these operation-node properties:

```
//! - `parallel: Bool` — when `true`, the evaluator invokes the body on
//!   each element concurrently via `std::thread::scope`. Ordering of the
//!   accumulated result list is preserved.
//! - `batch_size: Int` — chunk size for capability re-checking
//!   (cooperating with `benten_caps::DEFAULT_BATCH_BOUNDARY`).
```

`grep 'parallel\|batch_size' crates/benten-eval/src/primitives/iterate.rs` returns only those two comment lines. Neither property is read by `execute` — the body is never dispatched at all (it's property-driven in Phase 1), and the re-check boundary comes from `host.iterate_batch_boundary()` which has no per-op override path.

Additionally, line 33-37 of the same module docstring correctly reveals that 'The Phase-1 executor does not dispatch a body subgraph (no engine handle is in scope)' — this makes the earlier `parallel` bullet doubly wrong (you cannot run something in parallel that isn't running at all).

emit.rs:32-34 promises:

```
/// Routes the emit through [`PrimitiveHost::emit_event`] so the engine's
/// change-broadcast can fan it out. Returns `"ok"` unconditionally; EMIT is
/// fire-and-forget and never surfaces subscriber failures.
```

The Engine's impl at benten-engine/src/primitive_host.rs:248-253:

```rust
fn emit_event(&self, _name: &str, _payload: Value) {
    // Phase-1 EMIT is a no-op at the host level — ...
}
```

The module doc at emit.rs:17-19 acknowledges 'The real `ChangeBroadcast` wiring lands alongside the engine handle in G7; until then this executor honours the fire-and-forget edge contract without touching the broadcast.' G7 has shipped, but the wiring did not land — the host impl remains a no-op and the EMIT primitive's advertised behavior (fan-out to change-broadcast) does not happen.

This is softer than the other aspirational findings because (a) the module doc does flag it, and (b) the fire-and-forget contract is itself preserved — `"ok"` routes correctly. But the function-level doc at line 32-34 is still wrong: the emit is NOT fanned out to the change broadcast. Downgrading from major because the module-level self-awareness partially covers it.

call.rs:18-21 says:

```
//! Phase-1 scope: the executor does not actually invoke a callee subgraph
//! (no engine handle available); it validates the attenuation + timeout
//! preconditions and surfaces the edge-routing decision. G7 wires up the
//! real invocation path.
```

But the execute() body at lines 110-133 DOES invoke the callee:

```rust
if let (Some(Value::Text(target)), Some(Value::Text(callee_op))) =
    (op.properties.get("target"), op.properties.get("call_op"))
{
    let input = Node::empty();
    match host.call_handler(target, callee_op, input) {
        Ok(v) => return Ok(StepResult { ... edge_label: "ok", output: v }),
        Err(EvalError::Capability(c)) => return Ok(StepResult { ... edge_label: "ON_DENIED", ... }),
        Err(e) => return Err(e),
    }
}
```

The Engine's `impl PrimitiveHost::call_handler` at primitive_host.rs:222-246 recursively calls `dispatch_call`. So CALL **does** invoke the callee (when `target` + `call_op` properties are staged) — contradicting the module doc's 'Phase-1 scope' claim. The comment at line 135 hedges ('Legacy no-target path: Phase-1 fixtures that only stage attenuation / timeout properties still work') but the dominant path (the one every real registered handler hits) is fully wired.

iterate.rs:33-37:

```
//! The Phase-1 executor does not dispatch a body subgraph (no engine
//! handle is in scope); iteration is accounted for the cap-refresh cadence
//! only. The returned `output` is an empty accumulator list, same as the
//! pre-compromise-#1 shape, so existing tests that pin the happy-path
//! output remain green.
```

The first clause ('Phase-1 executor does not dispatch a body subgraph') is TRUE and verified against the code. But the parenthetical '(no engine handle is in scope)' is wrong — the `host: &dyn PrimitiveHost` parameter has been in scope since G6 restructured around PrimitiveHost. The real reason the body isn't dispatched is 'not required by any Phase-1 test subgraph' — the host surface has the `call_handler` primitive that would enable it.

This is minor because the outer claim (no body dispatch) is accurate. The justification, however, is stale: it references the pre-PrimitiveHost world.
